(125, 'Paperclip Fusion Point Express', '<p>The reset button is located to the bottom right of the front label. It is positioned on the black plastic face, where the seams of the device meet.</p>\r\n<p><img src=\"upload/fpxPinhole.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"640\" height=\"111\" /></p>\r\n<p>To \"paperclip\" the device, have the caller locate the pinhole and gently insert a straightened paperclip into the hold until they feel the click of a button being depressed.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Have the caller hold the button down until the Activity light illuminates on the FPX.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>After the Activity light comes on, have the caller remove the paperclip.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><span style=\"color: #ff0000;\"><strong>WARNING: Holding down the button longer can result in a \"bricked\" device, meaning it had been defaulted to factory settings and will no longer be usable.<br />Most bricked devices have to be replaced via EQR from TNS.</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Paperclipping a&nbsp;Fusion Point&nbsp;does a few things:<br /><br /></span><span style=\"color: #000000;\">It will force the FPX to send logs to TNS as long as the FPX is online and it will also&nbsp;force the FPX to pull down and load any configuration changes made by the TNS helpdesk.</span></p>', '2012-09-19 10:46:03', 'l7d23b', '2017-03-23 08:51:11', 'l7d23b', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Procedure for paperclipping a Fusion Point Express FPX', '', 30009, 'Tech Support 1', 'N', ''),
