(273, 'Verifone Commander / Ruby CI on Sagenet Prysm', '<h3>Commander /&nbsp;CI&nbsp;Settings and Connections:</h3>\r\n<table style=\"height: 129px;\" border=\"1\" width=\"100%\" cellspacing=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 59px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 81%; height: 59px;\" colspan=\"6\">\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Commander IP Setup information for Spacenet Prysm:</span></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>SSL security settings must be set to disabled</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 13px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 27%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ebecf0;\" colspan=\"2\"><strong>Isolated Payment NIC</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 25%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ebecf0;\" colspan=\"2\"><strong>Device Specific Routes</strong></td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 29%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ebecf0;\" colspan=\"2\"><strong>Buypass Config</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 13px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 10%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ebecf0;\">IP&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 17%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid;\">192.168.1.30</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 10%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ebecf0;\">Route Type</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 15%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid;\">Host</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 13.88%; height: 13.62px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ebecf0;\">Connection Mode&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 15.11%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid;\">IP</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 13px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 10%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ebecf0;\">Gateway</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 17%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid;\">192.168.1.254</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 10%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ebecf0;\">Destination</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 15%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid;\">204.194.125.9</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 13.88%; height: 13.62px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ebecf0;\">IP</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 15.11%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid;\">204.194.125.9</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 13.62px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 10%; height: 13.62px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ebecf0;\">Netmask</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 17%; height: 13.62px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid;\">255.255.255.0</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 10%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ebecf0;\">Gateway</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 15%; height: 13.62px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid;\">192.168.1.254</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 13.88%; height: 13.62px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ebecf0;\">Port</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 15.11%; height: 13.62px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid;\">7735</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr style=\"height: 13px;\">\r\n<td style=\"width: 10%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 17%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 10%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ebecf0;\">Netmask</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 15%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid;\">255.255.255.255</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 13.88%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td style=\"width: 15.11%; height: 13px; border-bottom-color: grey; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: solid;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<strong>***NOTE: IF 192.168.1.30 Does not work in the payment&nbsp;NIC&nbsp;try ip address 192.168.1.25.***</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Important Information:</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Please note that dashes should <strong>never</strong> be entered as part of the merchant ID. To verify the correct Merchant ID was entered, check the merchant ID from an EPS configuration report to confirm it was entered correctly.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>The <strong>Cybera Enhanced Zone Router</strong> allows Verifone to remotely connect to the Commander. If the site was supplied with this device it MUST be connected to LAN3 on the Prysm. Connecting this device directly to an open internet connection can&nbsp;expose the card payment application to the internet. This is a massive security risk.</li>\r\n<li>The Cisco 800 series solution for TNS has a dial back up that comes with it.&nbsp; It is an <span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><em><span style=\"font-size: 10pt;\"><strong>external dial back up modem</strong></span></em></span> that connects to the <strong>\"AUX\" </strong>port on the Cisco router.</li>\r\n<li>&nbsp;If a site is unable to pull a parameter download (PDL), please have the tech confirm the merchant ID.&nbsp; The letters in the merchant ID have to be uppercase.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Commander Connections</h3>\r\n<p><img style=\"margin-right: auto; margin-left: auto; display: block;\" src=\"upload/commander-prysm.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"786\" height=\"786\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h3>Ruby CI Connections</h3>\r\n<p><img style=\"margin-right: auto; margin-left: auto; display: block;\" src=\"upload/ci-prysm.PNG\" alt=\"\" width=\"787\" height=\"717\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2014-06-11 15:23:00', 'l7d23b', '2017-02-07 13:05:14', 'l7d23b', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Commander / CI Setup Information', '', 10010, 'Tech Support 1', 'N', ''),
(274, 'GemPay Pinpad Extension Cables', '<p>If you have a site that has a &ldquo;Night Hatch&rdquo; and the cable that is connected to the Pinpad from the Gempay is not long enough, HTEC does provide a extension cable that they can mail to the site.&nbsp; Simply give HTEC a call or open a ticket in Metro and request a extension cable be sent to the store.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>', '2014-06-18 08:21:50', 'l7d23b', '2017-09-18 10:51:45', 'l7d23b', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'GemPay Pinpad Extension Cables', '', 80003, 'UK Support 1', 'N', ''),
(275, 'Ops Manual 3 - Valero Card Services', '<p><strong>3 Valero Card Services</strong><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"upload/ops11.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"734\" height=\"832\" /></p>\r\n<p>Figure 1: VCS Service Provider Overview</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The Valero Card Services scheme provides a consolidated card package for Valero retail sites in the UK. Valero bulk-buys card services from providers, and the Valero network strenght and transaction volume ensure that Valero receives preferential rates, and keeps the costs of transactions to sites low. These costs manifiest themselves largely in merchant service charges (MSCs) levied on sites for every sigle card transaction that passes through the site. Valero negotiated rates are relatively lower than what sites would get on their own, and represents an important driver for sites to sign up for the brand.</p>\r\n<p><br />Valero is billed for the merchant charges and other anciliary service charges by the service providers, and would recharge the sites for the services retrospectively at the end of the month following the month of use. Sites would generally fall under two broad cathegories for VCS billing:</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: upper-roman;\">\r\n<li>Capped charges: Sites with capping refer to sites with committed volume sales over an agreed period, and agreements are reached to cap their VCS charges to a certain percentage provided they meet their committed sale volume. If they fail to make the agreed volume,the full capping charge comes into force as if the capping agreement had never been entered into.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Full recharge: Sites that are not on capping arrangements, and pay their VCS bill 30 days after the month of use.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;<br /><br /><strong>3.1 THE VCS PARTNERS/SUPPLIERS</strong><br />This refers to the various suppliers that support the VCS proposition:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><strong>ATOS</strong><br />Legacy polling bureau provider, and current provider of the TCS helpdesk. ATOS also downloads loyalty update files unto sites, and builds the settlement files on non-retail tech refresh sites . <br /><br /></li>\r\n<li><strong>BarclayCard (BMS)</strong><br />Barclaycard is the Bank Merchant acquirer, responsible for authorising all visa credit and debit card transactions on sites. Barclays settles transactions to sites, and goes back to the individual issuing backs to recoup settled transaction totals. The BMS contract is with Valero, and Valero settles the bank merchant charges to BMS, and recoups it from retailers through VCS billing.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li><strong>Card terminal providers</strong><br />There are two major terminal providers on the VCS estate:<ol>\r\n<li>Gempay ADSL terminals by HTEC</li>\r\n<li>Gemini ISDN terminals provided by HTEC<br /><br />The Gemini is a legacy terminal and will not be used on the Valero estate after the Gempay rollout.<br /><br /></li>\r\n</ol></li>\r\n<li><strong>Online Authorisation (OLA)</strong><br />This is the switiching function that allows transactions to go to the bank and card issuers for authorisation. There is a click-charge for transaction authorisation for every request.<br />There are two OLA hosts on the network at the moment<br /><br /><ol style=\"list-style-type: upper-roman;\">\r\n<li>FIS: The broadband host, authorises all broadband-site transactions and all fuel card cross-acceptance transactions. This supplier is the strategic choice to support OLA in the near future, and will also take over the functio of developing the settlement file.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Retail Decisions (RED): Legacy authorisation host, supports the legacy ISDN authorisation process. The RED host will not be used after the Gempay rollout is completed<br /><br /></li>\r\n</ol></li>\r\n<li><strong>Comms Providers</strong><br /><br /><ol style=\"list-style-type: upper-roman;\">\r\n<li>BT is responsible for providing ISDN lines, and ISDN orders are placed with the BT order centre <a href=\"mailto:Customer.Order.Team.Edinburgh@bt.com\">Customer.Order.Team.Edinburgh@bt.com</a> or 0808 100 7243. You must allow 30 days for an ISDN order to be delivered, even though BT tends to deliver in 3 weeks.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>TNS (Transaction network services): Delivers ADSL services, and the PSTN lines they run on. TNS is also responsible for the router prep. Orders are placed with the TNS Account team through <a href=\"mailto:NCorker@tnsi.com\">NCorker@tnsi.com</a>. Again allow not less than 30 days for the order to be fulfilled.</li>\r\n</ol></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>3.2 THE BRAND</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The Valero retail brand is Texaco in the UK and the republic of Ireland. Sites brand with Texaco when they sign a fuel supply deal with Valero. These deals last 5 years, and at the end of the period a site can sign a new deal with Valero, or chose to go to another brand.<br />Branded sites also sign the VCS agreement for the supply of card services, and the VCS agreement is tied to the fuel supply agreement. VCS is only available in the UK, and only on Texaco-branded sites.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>3.3 BRANDING, NON-BRANDING AND FUEL AGREEMENTS</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Valero has different fuel supply agreements. There are big dealers who take fuel from Valero and resell to sites. These sites are branded Texaco, but the fuel agreement is with the dealer, not Valero. These dealers are described as authorised distributors, and Valero offers sites with agreements with these dealers Valero card services as well. VCS is not offered to unbranded sites.</p>', '2014-07-28 06:13:03', 'l7d23b', '2014-07-30 07:29:33', 'l7d23b', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Card Systems Operations and Maintenance Manual', '', 80002, 'Tech Support 1', 'N', 'mailto:Customer.Order.Team.Edinburgh@bt.commailto:NCorker@tnsi.com'),
(276, 'Ops Manual 4 - Card Systems', '<h4><strong>4 CARD SYSTEMS</strong></h4>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Card systems describe the technology and processes currently employed for providing card services to Valero retailers who participate in the Valero Card services scheme. Card systems include the infrastructure and communications required for supporting the VCS scheme.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>4.1 EFT, EPOS<br /><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">EPOS refers to the electronic point of sale equipment used for taking payments on sites. The EPOS traditionally allows sites to take cash payments and run reconciliation of transaction totals. Usually connected to an internal network or local area network, the modern POS is a windows-based device capable of sending data between networks and in the simplest form, returning reconciliation data to the back office. <br />Within the UK VCS environment, there are a number of sites with modern POS systems where the POS takes not only cash transactions, but also card payments. These POS systems are described as &ldquo;integrated POS&rdquo;, alluding to the integration of POS and electronic fund transfer capabilities in a single device.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The EFT provides the capability to take card transactions, differentiate between different card schemes, rules and card types, and sits in a different device in the majority of VCS sites in the UK. The exception is the integrated POS, where, as explained above, the EFT and POS software sit on the same device.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>4.2 TYPES OF TERMINALS</strong><br /><br /></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Terminals are used where EFT and EPOS are not integrated in the same device. In the UK, the bulk of sites use terminals for taking card transactions. There are currently two types of terminals used in the UK today:</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The Gemini terminal: this is the legacy terminal running on ISDN. The Gemini is supplied and maintained by HTEC. It can run either linked to the POS, or in standalone mode. <br /><br /></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The GemPAY Terminal which is currently being rolled out across the Valero UK estate. Expected completion is on or before Q4 2014</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>4.2.1 Types of Terminal links<br /><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">A link is the connection between the terminal and the point of sale. Stand-alone terminals are terminals that are unlinked/connected to any payment device on site.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">There are 2 ways of linking terminals on site:</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>OPI/software link: See section 4.8 for a more detailed functional description of this type of terminal. This refers to the software link between integration-capable points of sale and the Gempay terminal.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>F75/Serial link: Serial interface providing a link between the Gempay and the POS. In this instance, the POS does not have to be capable of integration.<br /><br /><br /></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><strong>4.3 TYPES OF POS<br /><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Two key types:<br /><br /></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Integrated, VCS-certified POS: <br /><br /><span style=\"color: #800080;\">Pos currently existing in integrated mode will be migrated to run the Gempay using the OPI link.</span><br /><br />\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Micros Iridium<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>HTEC Hydrapos<br /><br /><br /></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Others:<br /><br /><span style=\"color: #800080;\">These are the older or VCS un-certified POS, and will usually be deployed either in linked mode or in standalone mode</span><br /><span style=\"color: #800080;\">Valero does not dictate POS for use on retail sites, and will not look to integrate from the POS.</span><br /><br />\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Gilbarco Passport<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Edacom (ICL)<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Softoptions (Indigo Retail)<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>FuelPoS (Tokheim)<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Micrelec Master series, SmartPoS (VBI)<br /><br /><br /></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>4.4 LEGACY TECHNOLOGY VS TECHNOLOGY REFRESH<br /><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Legacy technology refers to the current stack of integrated POS, and Gemini EFT terminals currently in use in the Texaco network.<br />In 2011, the decision was made to swap out the current terminals and replace them with a new, ADSL-based terminal as standard. This decision was driven by two key factors:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The need to reduce the number of suppliers involved in developing and supporting card systems across the board, and find some economies of scale across the existing model<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Update the current technology (which is mostly end of life) and improve the performance and responsiveness of technology in the face of changes in the industry, thereby driving down costs and improving reliability.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br />The project responsible for delivering this change is the Retail Technology refresh project, and new terminals delivered as part of the project are described as refresh terminals.</p>\r\n<p><br />Refresh terminals are the GemPay terminals, supplied by HTEC (same company that gave us the Gemini). The Refresh terminal is deployed across ADSL with a GPRS fallback, and can function in any of the three modes described below:</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>Integrated to the POS through an API interface: this allows the POS to run transactions as if the GemPay was not connected to it, but all the time taking instructions on card transactions from the terminal. In look and feel, it is pretty similar to the integrated POS described in 3.1<br /><br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Linked mode: This is where the terminal is linked to the POS through a serial cable, running the F75 protocol. This means that the transactions are taken through the till, but there is a hand-off that happens when the mode of payment is card, thereby allowing the card terminal to take the payment.<br /><br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Stand-alone mode: where the till is so old that it cannot support integration or linking, or on single POS sites where the terminal is a backup terminal,&nbsp; the terminal will be deployed in standalone mode. In this case card transactions are cancelled on the till, and taken through the terminal. These sites will also get an extra terminal connected to the network and ready for use in case the main terminal is out of service for any length of time. This back-up terminal will usually be deployed in stand-alone mode, connected to the network and with a heart beat that can be monitored even when not in use.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>4.5&nbsp;INTEGRATED POINTS OF SALE:<br /><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Where the POS is integrated, both the EFT and ePOS run on the POS. This implies a duality of card and cash payment capability on a single device.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>There is no separate terminal for EFT<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>The POS will have a PIN-entry device attached to it</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><br />In the future when the transition to the GemPay is completed, this phrase will be used to describe terminals integrated into the POS via the API software module.</p>\r\n<p><br />There are only 2 legacy POS systems that can be integrated today:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>The HTEC Hydrapos POS<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>The Torex Iridium</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Post the deployment of the GemPay terminal, integration will be driven through the terminal and not the POS. To enable the integration, a software solution will be deployed as an application protocol interface to provide the terminal interface and graphics on the POS, whilst the EFT capability sits on the terminal. Please note that this capability will only be deployed on POS systems which are currently integrated. All POS systems that currently function as linked solutions with the Gemini terminal will also be deployed in linked mode with the GemPay.</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>4.6&nbsp;TERMINALS IN LINKED MODE<br /><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">See 4.2 and 4.4 (b)</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>4.7&nbsp;STANDALONE TERMINALS<br /><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">See 4.2 and 4.4 (c)<br /><br /></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>4.8&nbsp;THE GEMPAY TERMINAL<br /><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The Gempay is the current strategic EFT solution Valero is deploying in the UK. Built on a Gemalto Terminal solution, it is ADSL-capable, and replaces both the current Gemini-linked terminals and the integrated Point of sale EFT solutions. <br />The GemPAY terminal runs multiple applications accepting several different card ranges for both EMV and fuel cards.&nbsp; The terminal configuration is controlled by the Terminal Management System (TMS).&nbsp; The terminal uses the HappEFT application to accept EMV cards and uses the Fuelcards_8583 application to accept the fuel cards to meet Valero requirements.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><br />The software has been developed to use strong industry-standard data security capabilities (triple DES encryption).<br />The terminal is connected to a POS over TCP/IP or a serial communication channel. The Host connection is via TCP/IP using SSL encryption.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>There are three main configuration options to use GemPAY for the said solution.</p>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: square;\">\r\n<li>A separate USB Keyboard can be used with Options 2 and 3 to aid cashier with VRN and Mileage entry.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: upper-roman;\">\r\n<li><strong>Option 1 &ndash; XML over TCP/IP to POS Interface (OPI Mode)<br /><br /><img src=\"upload/opi.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"338\" height=\"211\" /><br /></strong>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: circle;\">\r\n<li>GemPAY faces the cashier</li>\r\n<li>PIN pad faces the cardholder</li>\r\n<li>Transaction entry is on the POS</li>\r\n<li>EFT messages and cashier input on the POS</li>\r\n<li>VRN &amp; mileage entry is on the POS</li>\r\n<li>EFT receipts are printed on the POS printer</li>\r\n<li>PIN entry and card insertion is on the PIN pad</li>\r\n<li>Card swipe is on the terminal<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><strong>Option 2 &ndash; Legacy Protocol (F75 or A77.03) Support (Linked mode)<br /><img src=\"upload/f75.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"338\" height=\"211\" /><br /></strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>GemPAY faces the cashier</li>\r\n<li>PIN Pad faces the cardholder</li>\r\n<li>Transaction entry is on the POS</li>\r\n<li>EFT messages and cashier input on the terminal</li>\r\n<li>VRN &amp; mileage entry is on the terminal (Txt style for VRN)</li>\r\n<li>EFT receipts are printed on the terminal printer</li>\r\n<li>PIN entry and card insertion is on the PIN Pad</li>\r\n<li>Card swipe is on the terminal<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><strong>Option 3 &ndash; Stand Alone Mode (single or unsupported POS)<br /><img src=\"upload/standalone.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"338\" height=\"211\" /><br /></strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>GemPAY faces the cashier</li>\r\n<li>PIN Pad faces the cardholder</li>\r\n<li>Transaction entry is on the POS and terminal</li>\r\n<li>EFT messages and cashier input on the terminal</li>\r\n<li>VRN &amp; mileage entry is on the terminal (Txt style for VRN)</li>\r\n<li>EFT receipts are printed on the terminal printer</li>\r\n<li>PIN entry and card insertion is on the PIN Pad</li>\r\n<li>Card swipe is on the terminal</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>', '2014-07-29 08:15:59', 'l7d23b', '2014-07-30 07:29:19', 'l7d23b', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Card Systems Operations and Maintenance Manual', '', 80002, 'UK Support 1', 'N', ''),
(277, 'Ops Manual 5 - Card Types', '<p><strong>5&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;CARD TYPES</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">All card types are identified by their ISO ranges and PAN numbers, usually represented as part of the long card number displayed on the front of the card. These ISO ranges are provided and maintained on the Valero card scheme rules, which are a set of ranges agreed under contract between Valero and the card issuers for use on Valero sites. Online authorisation of card transactions checks that the card presented for payment on the site is either on the range for acceptance on the network, a valid card and not on the hot card list (list of cards suspected of fraud).</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><br />For a copy of the Valero Card scheme rules, please follow the link below:</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><br /><a href=\"http://intranet.valero.com/IS/UKI1TeamSite/RetailTechnology/Shared%20Documents/Card%20Scheme%20Rules/Card%20scheme%20and%20till%20link%20grouping%20effective%2020120401.xlsx\">http://intranet.valero.com/IS/UKI1TeamSite/RetailTechnology/Shared%20Documents/Card%20Scheme%20Rules/Card%20scheme%20and%20till%20link%20grouping%20effective%2020120401.xlsx</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>There are 4 card types accepted on the Valero service stations:</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>5.1&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;COMMERCIAL CREDIT, DEBIT CARDS</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">These include visa and MasterCard debit /credit, commercial and premium cards, and American express cards.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>5.2&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;STARREWARDS LOYALTY CARDS</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The Valero UK loyalty program is called Starrewards. This is a swipe card only, and points are awarded for fuel purchases (points per litre) only. Cash, card and fuel card payments attract Starrewards points, but not bunker cards (qualifying transactions). To ensure transactions don&rsquo;t attract fraud, the terminal or card acceptance device (CAD) holds a detailed product list and validates the payment request against the Starreward loyalty product map.<br /><br />On legacy sites, the loyalty files are downloaded onto the terminal during the polling process, and points are shown on customer receipts after transactions on site.<br /><br />On the sites that have been updated as part of the retail refresh, the approach is different. Loyalty is treated as any other card transaction, and the point update is returned with response from the OLA host at the completion of a successful transaction.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>5.3&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;FUEL CARDS</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">These include Valero Fastfuel and The Business card, and other fuel card schemes Valero has contracted to accept on the Texaco network. The lists of accepted cards are on the card scheme rules, which are updated as appropriate as new schemes are added to it.<br />Fleet car companies and trucking firms use fuel cards to manage fuel usage on their fleet, and include bunker cards&nbsp; and fleet cards. The advantages of fuel cards include discounts, tracking vehicle and fuel use, network reach, etc.<br />Most fuel cards are swiped on Texaco sites. Currently, Allstar is the only fuel card company in the UK working at developing a chip and pin based fuel card.<br /><br />The fuel card acceptance guide is on:<br /><a href=\"http://intranet.valero.com/IS/UKI1TeamSite/RetailTechnology/Shared%20Documents/Fuel%20Card%20Acceptance%20Guide%202014%20v3.pdf\">http://intranet.valero.com/IS/UKI1TeamSite/RetailTechnology/Shared%20Documents/Fuel%20Card%20Acceptance%20Guide%202014%20v3.pdf</a><br /><br /></p>\r\n<p><strong>5.4&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;LOCAL ACCOUNT CARDS</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">These are usually site-issued cards, and are not accepted on the Gempay or the Valero terminal. Sites would usually process these cards on their tills. This includes Compower cards.<br /><br /></p>', '2014-07-29 10:32:31', 'l7d23b', '2014-08-19 10:40:15', 'l7d23b', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Card Systems Operations and Maintenance Manual', '', 80002, 'UK Support 1', 'N', 'http://intranet.valero.com/IS/UKI1TeamSite/RetailTechnology/Shared Documents/Card Scheme Rules/Card scheme and till link grouping effective 20120401.xlsxhttp://intranet.valero.com/IS/UKI1TeamSite/RetailTechnology/Shared Documents/Fuel Card Acceptance Guide 2014 v3.pdf'),
(278, 'Ops Manual 6 - Legacy Polling', '<p><strong>6&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;LEGACY POLLING</strong></p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>6.1&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;WHAT IS POLLING?</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">In legacy sites, card transactions are held on the terminal or the POS (whichever holds the EFT capability) until they are picked up through the polling process. ATOS is the polling bureau, and polls sites to gather up transaction files by dialing into the EFT device and picking up the transaction files. Polling occurs once a day (at midnight or just before), and would last a few minutes. Transactions polled from the site are built into a settlement file which is submitted to the Bank Merchant Acquirer and all other card issuers for payment to the site. If there are discrepancies between the polled transactions and the bank&rsquo;s authorisation records for the same period, the bank will refuse to settle on the disputed transactions.<br />Polling is a function of legacy sites. Sites on technology refresh will batch the transaction records at the end of day, and push these out to the settlement host, thereby removing the need to poll entirely.</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>6.2&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;ADDRESSING POLLING FAILURES</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">There are currently between 7 and 8 percent failures on polling every night in the legacy network. There are several factors that drive polling failures:</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>Polling is monitored using Texaco polling failure and management reports provided by ATOS on a daily basis. These reports identify sites that have not polled and provide what is believed to be the reason for the failure. These failure reasons are not always accurate and easy to decipher, but they do offer a good indication to how often the site has failed. The loyalty download failures report is also provided as part of the failure reporting.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>The simplest cause of failure is the failure of the site to perform an end of day process. The end of day helps the terminal /EFT run site reconciliation on its own transactions and prepares the data for collection by the polling agent. If the site has not completed the end of day, the data cannot be polled.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Polling uses either a PSTN (broadband sites) or ISDN phone lines. If there is a fault on the line, polling will fail. Where the support analyst fails to identify a reason for polling failures, the expectation is that a test is carried out on the line. Polling is flaky and will fail; the support organisation will monitor it and treat these occasional failures as bleeps. Once failure occurs more than twice on consecutive nights on the same site, it is treated as unusual. The support analyst should work with ATOS to identify why the failure is happening and instigate corrective action.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Once it is determined that the site has failed to poll on a number of nights, please arrange for the terminal supplier to carry out a manual poll of the site.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Again where polling failures occur regularly and without any obvious signs as to cause, please check the baud rate setting on the modem and perhaps arrange to have that changed, Another handy trick is also to ask the polling bureau to change the polling window.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><br /><span style=\"color: #800080;\"><strong>Please Note: Polling is a legacy process and will no longer be supported as soon as all sites are migrated to the Gempay terminal.</strong></span><br /><br /></p>', '2014-07-29 10:37:35', 'l7d23b', '2014-07-30 07:28:46', 'l7d23b', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Card Systems Operations and Maintenance Manual', '', 80002, 'UK Support 1', 'N', ''),
(279, 'Ops Manual 7 - Transactions and Settlement', '<p><strong>7&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;TRANSACTIONS, SETTLEMENT AND MISSING TRANSACTIONS</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>7.1&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;THE BANK MERCHANT ACQUIRER AND CARD ISSUERS</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The bank merchant acquirer is responsible for authorizing and settling all visa credit and debit transactions. The current BMS on Valero sites is Barclaycard, who also acquire MasterCard transactions. The BMS will authorize and settle the transactions back to the retailer. Reconciliation with other banks is done through the clearing process.<br />Other card issuers include the entire fuel card issuers accepted on the Valero network, who would usually authorize their own cards. American Express is also a card issuer and would again authorize and settle its own transactions.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>7.2&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;ONLINE AUTHORISATION AND TRANSACTION SWITCHING</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The online authorisation process is important because the BMS will not accept direct requests for authorisation from the sites. The switch will accept the request for authorisation from the site, switch to the BMS or card issuer, and send the response back to the site. <br />In legacy sites, the OLA host performs the transaction switching whilst the polling bureau builds the settlement file. In the new refreshed environment, the OLA switch performs the settlement filing and switching function.<br />There are currently 2 OLA hosts in the Valero network:<br />FIS (Certegy) for the sites using ADSL for OLA<br />Retail Decisions (RED) for the legacy ISDN sites<br />Most ISDN transactions are routed through RED for authorisation. However along with all ADSL transactions, all fuel card cross-acceptance transactions and a few ISDN transactions are now routing through FIS as well. The FIS host is seen as resilient and most sites are migrated to FIS when there are difficulties connecting to the RED host.<br />At the completion of the Retail Technology Refresh project, all sites will be using the FIS host for OLA.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>7.3&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;SETTLEMENT FILES</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">On legacy sites, settlement files are built by the polling bureau and submitted to the bank merchant acquirer and card issuers. The files picked up from the sites during the polling process are built into settlement files and used by the bank and card issuers for reconciling authorisation requests against the completed transactions from the sites. The banks will not settle un-reconciled transactions. Settlement is complete when the funds are paid into the retailer&rsquo;s account. Polling reports are emailed to sites on a daily basis.<br />On sites that have been migrated over to Gempay, the settlement file is built by the OLA switch (FIS). Copies of settlement reports are stored on the Texaco Station extranet and sites can download these reports. They are weekly reports, with details of daily settlements for the past week.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>7.3.1&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;How to Access Settlement files from Texaco Station</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Gempay sites are not polled. The transaction records are forwarded by the terminal every day as part of the end of day process. <br />Settlement reports are the equivalent of polling reports, and are produced every week to show a complete breakdown of transactions from the sites which have been submitted for payment. Retailers on Gempay can access their Settlement Reports from Texaco Station, www.TexacoStation.com, All retailers have access to this site as they use it to order fuel, etc.&nbsp; For head office personnel who require access they can do so by clicking the &ldquo;Register or Request Access&rdquo; link at the welcome page:<br /><br /><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"upload/texportal01.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"612\" height=\"346\" /><br />&nbsp;<br /><br />To access Settlement Reports for Gempay terminals retailers need to select &ldquo;Settlement Reports&rdquo; on the E-Billing menu:<br />&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;<br /><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"upload/texportal02.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"584\" height=\"270\" /></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>7.4&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;TROUBLE SHOOTING MISSING TRANSACTIONS</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">There are so many instances where transactions can be described as missing. When the banks do not have a record of the transaction, or the transaction is not picked up on the settlement file, the transaction will not settle. This could happen where the transaction is not polled, or does not form part of the polling segment for the day, which usually completes by midnight. In this case the transactions could form part of the settlement files for the next day. BMS contracts to settle on the day the settlement files are received + 2 working days.<br />On legacy sites, transactions could be stuck in the terminal, or just not captured at all. On occasions like that, a manual poll can be arranged with the polling bureau and terminal supplier to retrieve the transactions. Where the volume of transactions stuck in the terminal is so big that a manual poll cannot successfully retrieve all of them, the terminal supplier will be asked to retrieve the transaction files and send them to the settlement host.<br />On retail technology refreshed sites, the option of a manual poll will not exist. Where there is a terminal failure and the end of day cannot be run on the terminal, the settlement host will be asked to settle the transactions held for that site. Send an email to ccshelpdesk.uk@fisglobal.com, and copy Paul.Holden@fisglobal.com.<br />This process is mostly used where the terminal has failed (mostly security tamper) and been recovered by HTEC.<br />Where the issue is that card transactions have gone through the terminal, and there are disputes as to authorisation, the FIS customer database (WREN) keeps a record of all transactions that pass through FIS by card number and site. One can easily log on to WREN and with details of the time of the transaction determine what the card type is and what the amount of the transaction was. WREN will also tell you whether the transaction went through successfully or was declined. On legacy sites not going through FIS, Retail Decisions can provide the same details, albeit it not online.<br />On refreshed sites, please make sure the site is not showing up on the end of day failure reports FIS send:</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: upper-roman;\">\r\n<li>If the site is on the end of day failure report, please send the site an email to do their end of day, detailing the terminal and transaction amount (The UK Technology team sends out an update on a daily basis advising defaulting sites to run their end of day)<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>If the site shows up on FIS&rsquo;s suspense report, it indicates there are transactions held in suspense. Transactions are usually held in suspense when FIS cannot reconcile them. Please find out why the transactions are in suspense, ask FIS helpdesk to release the transactions and if there is a terminal fault that has pushed the transaction into suspense, raise that with HTEC as a fault.<br />Send any requests to release transactions to the FIS helpdesk at:<br /><a href=\"mailto:ccshelpdesk.uk@fisglobal.com\">ccshelpdesk.uk@fisglobal.com</a> and copy Paul Holden at <a href=\"mailto:Paul.Holden@fisglobal.com\">Paul.Holden@fisglobal.com</a></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Please note:</strong></span><br />Every time an end of day is done on site, the transaction summary is sent to FIS who use this to build the settlement file, and trickle the messages to the acquirers and card issuers. If the terminal fails to trickle for whatever reason, the terminal will be withdrawn, and FIS is asked to release the files from the site for settlement as the terminal cannot trickle. Under no circumstances should we run an end of day on a withdrawn terminal. That will cause the transactions to be trickled again and could lead to a double-settlement.</p>\r\n<p><br />If a terminal is damaged and cannot trickle, HTEC will inform Valero, and Valero will in turn instruct the FIS CCS helpdesk to release the transactions: <a href=\"mailto:ccshelpdesk.uk@fisglobal.com\">ccshelpdesk.uk@fisglobal.com</a><br /><br /></p>', '2014-07-29 10:43:31', 'l7d23b', '2014-07-30 07:28:31', 'l7d23b', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Card Systems Operations and Maintenance Manual', '', 80002, 'UK Support 1', 'N', 'mailto:ccshelpdesk.uk@fisglobal.com');
INSERT INTO `article` (`artid`, `arttitle`, `artbody`, `createstamp`, `usercreate`, `modstamp`, `usermod`, `pubflag`, `rfcflag`, `comment`, `usercomment`, `commentstamp`, `summary`, `triggers`, `chainid`, `rolename`, `encflag`, `linkdoctext`) VALUES
(280, 'Ops Manual 8 - New Site Setup', '<div class=\"asumm\"><strong>8&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;NEW SITE SETUP</strong></div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The process of setting up a site happens either at a change of owner of an existing site, change of supply arrangements, or the sign-up of new sites to the Texaco brand</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\"><strong>8.1&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;SITE SETUP PROCESS:</strong></div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Proforma- initiates a VCS site management request from the field<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Order comms- Begins the order process for communications lines to support OLA.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Submit forms- Involves submitting completed documents received from the site to various acquirers<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Complete site survey- This involves getting site-specific information for equipment setup and installation. HTEC conducts the site survey on all sites.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Request TIDs- Starts the process of allocating terminal IDs to the CAD<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Approve/Provide MIDs- This response process is the approval or acknowledgement from the acquirer/card issuers based on acknowledgement of the application to join their schemes made by the prospective retailer.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Update SIF- The site information form contains all the relevant site data for all suppliers and acquirers/card issuers to action and bring site to live.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Circulate SIF- Circulate SIF as soon as completed . Usually sent by Merlin.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Confirm delivery of services- Acquirers and suppliers confirming services are delivered so site can go live.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Complete site set up (6 weeks SLA)- Total time is driven by speed of delivery of comms lines and infrastructure, acquirer/issuer approvals and terminal configuration and installation.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\"><strong>8.2&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;PROFORMA</strong></div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The Area Sales Manager raises the Proforma on Merlin (http://merlin/vcs) when a new site is added to the network, or an existing site goes through a change of owner or change of legal entity. The Proforma is raised on Merlin, and as soon as it is completed Merlin generates an email to the UK Technology team to send the Valero Card Services pack to the retailer, and notifies Retail Contract Support to assign a site number (if required) to start the site set up process.</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\"><strong>8.3&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;THE VCS PACK</strong>The VCS pack has forms for all the participating card issuers on the network:</div>\r\n<ul style=\"list-style-type: circle;\">\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">The BMS form, which includes the contract, the &ldquo;know your customer form&rdquo;, the direct debit mandate.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">The American express form<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">The Allstar form<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">The UKFuels form</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\">All the forms enclosed provide concise and clear instructions on how to fill them out. Not completing the forms correctly usually leads to delays in getting approvals from the issuers. <br /><br />&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\"><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"upload/sitemgmt-newsite.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"804\" height=\"805\" /></div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\"><strong>8.3.1&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;BMS forms</strong></div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Barclays requires that applicants must provide proof of identity (copy driver&rsquo;s license or passport and a bill). Where the applicant is trading as a limited liability company, the applicant must also provide directors&rsquo; proof of id (to a maximum of 4 directors), and proof of identity for anyone else holding 10% or more of the quoted shares of the company. This also extends to companies where shares are held in a trust. These details are required for the KYC process and will delay site set up if not provided.</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\"><strong>8.3.2&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;American Express</strong></div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Amex requires proof of identity of the applicants and a direct debit mandate. Forms must be signed and submitted to Amex along with the proof of identity, which is again a passport copy or driver&rsquo;s license, along with a copy of a valid utility bill.</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\"><strong>8.3.3&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;UKFuels</strong></div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The UKFuels forms require bank account details, address of the new site and signature of the applicant.</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\"><strong>8.3.4&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;Allstar</strong></div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The Allstar forms require bank account details, proof of identity and a copy of a valid VAT certificate.</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\"><strong>8.4&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;MERCHANT AND TERMINAL IDENTITY NUMBERS (MIDS AND TIDS)</strong></div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Merchant identify numbers are issued to the site by all the card issuers and the bank merchant acquirer. The MID is programmed into the card acceptance device and is used by the issuing card provider for identifying the site.</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><br />The Terminal ID (TID) is provided by the terminal/card acceptance device provider, and is programmed into the device. The TID for the site is aligned to the MID and forms part of the unique identifier for the site. All card transactions from the site bear the identifier of the MID and TID.</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><br />New sites and sites going through legal entity changes are expected to complete the VCS pack. The bank, AMEX and fuel card issuer forms are sent to each of the issuers. The issuers would usually take 10 days to generate the MIDs. Whilst the MID application is being processed, a survey of the site is carried out to determine what communication and card acceptance solutions the site will need.</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">On legacy sites, the decision on the terminal or card acceptance device to be used is made after the survey .&nbsp; Soon as the MIDs are received from the Bank Merchant acquirer and the card issuers, Merlin is updated. The request to the Terminal provider to generate the terminal ID must go as soon as the site survey is completed, before the SIF is distributed. The TIDs would usually take 48 hours to generate, and as soon as it is received the retail technology team updates Merlin.&nbsp; As soon as the MIDs and TIDs are in place, the site information form is generated and sent to the issuers, and suppliers; the SIF is the formal instruction requesting the set up of a site on an agreed date.</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">TID request, Terminal and engineering support for new sites:</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><br /><a href=\"mailto:installationrequest@htec.co.uk\">installationrequest@htec.co.uk</a></div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><br />Please note: There may also be a requirement to get POS support from Micros or Tokheim. This is on a site by site basis and the contacts are on the shared documents space on the Retail Technology SharePoint site.</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\"><strong>8.5&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;ORDERING TELECOMMS</strong></div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Request for phone lines should go in immediately after the site survey has been completed. It is key to put this order through as quickly as possible as the PSTN and ADSL order fulfillment could take as long as 35 days to complete . The current practice is to allow 30 days to order and deploy ADSL and PSTN. Where possible, this request should be completed as a simultaneous provision . PSTN orders require existing and known addresses. Where there are issues with the address, the service provider usually struggles to fulfill the order. We see this mostly where there are capacity issues, or the site is a Greenfield site.</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\"><strong>8.6&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;SITE SURVEY</strong></div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The site survey will tell the analyst how many terminals the site requires (1x1 relationship with the till on the site). The site survey also advises:</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Existing phone lines<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Captures site access details (opening/closing times, ease of access)<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">History (if any) of phone line challenges/historic difficulties with putting in lines (helps determine if there is a need for an additional survey for lines)<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Details all the phone numbers on the site</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">On the retail refresh sites, the PSTN/ADSL line request requires at least 30 days to fulfill. The line order may be made to TNS long before the survey is completed, and TNS will accept the request in lieu of the site information form.</p>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\"><strong>8.7&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;SITE READINESS PROCESS:</strong></div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\">The completion process follows a check 7 days before the site goes live, to ensure the site:</div>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Is on schedule to go live<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">All MIDs are set up<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Telecomms are installed<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Terminal(s) ready<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Engineers booked</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">At completion, all remaining documents (not required by the suppliers) must be either archived or destroyed. Data privacy laws dictate that documents containing personal information are locked away. Because the requisite information needed to manage the site is held in Merlin, there is no need to keep the documents.</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\"><strong>8.8&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;TROUBLE SHOOTING SITE SETUP</strong></div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">A few things can go wrong with a site set-up, not necessarily unrelated to challenges of managing sites post set-up. A few key frequently occurring issues include:</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: upper-roman;\">\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Lines are not ready: Mostly happens when the PSTN line order is late. On sites going through the technology refresh, if this is caught on time, the site can be set live using a GPRS router. If the site is in an area of poor GPRS signal, the go live will be delayed until PSTN line and ADSL services are delivered.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Wrong MIDS and/or TIDS: The site cannot get authorisation if the MIDs are not setup or associated with the TIDS at all issuers and the bank acquirer. The online authorisation host and terminal provider must also have the MIDs and TIDs setup on the terminal. If there are mismatches or the terminal is not set up to accept a particular card, the card will fail online authorisation.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li class=\"asumm\">Delays in issuing MIDs: This is pretty common. Most suppliers will take 10 days to issue MIDs. The rule of the thumb is to aim to complete as soon as the Barclays MID has been issued.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\"><strong>8.9&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;ARCHIVING SETUP DOCUMENTS</strong></div>\r\n<div class=\"asumm\" style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The only document the team retains at the completion of a site set up is the Valero Card Services site survey and registration document is usually retained and archived. It provides the initial information for determining the site&rsquo;s technology requirements, and is followed by a detailed site survey driven by Merlin<br /><br /></div>', '2014-07-29 11:58:26', 'l7d23b', '2014-07-30 07:28:15', 'l7d23b', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Card Systems Operations and Maintenance Manual', '', 80002, 'UK Support 1', 'N', 'mailto:installationrequest@htec.co.uk'),
(281, 'Ops Manual 9 - Site Closure', '<p><strong>9&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;SITE CLOSURE</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Site closure is kicked off by a Proforma. The Area Manager selects the closure type on the Proforma, and that generates a task to close the site.<br /><br /><br />There are 2 types of closures: Permanent/Debrand, and temporary closure.</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: upper-roman;\">\r\n<li>The permanent closure process instructs the card issuers, polling bureau and Bank Merchant acquirer to shut down and delete the MIDs on their system as the site is leaving the Texaco network. The permanent closure process also requires that the Valero card equipment on the site be retrieved by the terminal provider. This is less of an issue on legacy integrated sites because the card acceptance capability is integrated into the ePOS function which belongs to the retailer, so there is little input from the POS supplier outside deleting the MIDs. <br />Where the integrated site is on ADSL belonging to Valero, the ADSL lines should still be ceased and equipment recovered.&nbsp; In the event the line is ISDN, the site must confirm their desire to keep the line, in which case the line will be transferred to the site. In the absence of instruction to the contrary, the ISDN line will also be ceased. Where we cannot recover the equipment, we should bill the site for it through the VCS billing function.<br /><br />Issues here include the fact that as the terminal supplier (POS supplier in integrated sites) is responsible for deploying routers and comms infrastructure, they may not be available to recover the equipment when the site is closing. Post the tech refresh project, this will be easier to manage as all sites will have the GemPay EFT terminal, and permanent closures will be managed through a single process.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Temporary closure: Usually happens when the site is being refurbished. Depending on the length of time the site will be out of commission, the card issuers and bank acquirer will need to be informed, and may decide to shut down the MIDs and set the site up again when the site comes back into trade (as if it were a new site). This is likely to happen when the site is out for refurbishment for up to 6 months. Again the terminal supplier and comms provider will also need to be informed as lines may need to be suspended and terminals either recovered, or sites talked through disconnecting them and storing them safely until the site is back trading again.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2014-07-29 12:24:24', 'l7d23b', '2014-07-30 07:27:59', 'l7d23b', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Card Systems Operations and Maintenance Manual', '', 80002, 'UK Support 1', 'N', '');
INSERT INTO `article` (`artid`, `arttitle`, `artbody`, `createstamp`, `usercreate`, `modstamp`, `usermod`, `pubflag`, `rfcflag`, `comment`, `usercomment`, `commentstamp`, `summary`, `triggers`, `chainid`, `rolename`, `encflag`, `linkdoctext`) VALUES
(282, 'Ops Manual 10 - Supporting EFT', '<p><strong>10&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;SUPPORTING EFT</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Supporting EFT primarily means understanding the issues that have come up and troubleshooting those issues. As the environment is heavily reliant on 3rd party suppliers/vendors, it also helps to know who your key contacts are, and how to reach them.</p>\r\n<p><br /><strong>10.1&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;TROUBLESHOOTING EFT ISSUES</strong></p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: upper-roman;\">\r\n<li>Authorisation requests timing out: Comms failure. Raise with BT (on ISDN lines), or TNS (for ADSL/PSTN lines)<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Site polling failures: Are transactions going through? If yes, check what response the polling attempts are presenting. Reasons for polling failures include:<br /><br />\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>The site has failed to do a day end: Easily rectified, ask the site to do a day end the following night<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Fault on the phone line: This is harder to detect on broad band lines than on ISDN. Confirm line ownership. If the line belongs to Valero, raise the fault with the line provider. If the line is site-owned, the site must be instructed to raise the fault with their supplier. Broadband OLA lines always belong to Valero, supplied by TNS, who rarely acknowledge an issue on PSTN lines whilst the site has a good ADSL service. However there may still be a fault on the line though transactions are going ahead and authorizing on the ADSL service. <br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>General failure: Could be anything from equipment failure to line failure. Get the terminal supplier (Till provider on integrated sites) involved, and request a manual poll and a fix.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Too much data on the terminal/failed polls: Usual occurrence where the site has failed to poll for a while. Only way to retrieve the transactions would be to get the terminal provider to dial in and run a manual poll. In extreme cases, the terminal may be retrieved from site and files extracted at the provider&rsquo;s premises, and sent to the settlement host.<br /><br /></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Late payments on credit/debit transactions: Check with Barclays and ensure the site is set up to receive money on standard Valero terms (T+3= transaction day + 3). Sometimes Barclays gets it wrong and configures the payment terms outside the standard agreed timescales. Again when a site fails to poll, its transactions for the day do not form part of the settlement file submitted to Barclays, and Barclays will only settle on transactions it has received and validated on the settlement files.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>A card comes up with an invalid or unknown merchant: This means the card has not been set up for use on the site. Where the Bank or issuer has not set up the MID, or associated it with the TID on the card acceptance device, the card will present as merchant unknown. It could also mean that the MID is not set up on the terminal, or set up at the online authorisation host. Check with all parties and ensure the MIDs are set up.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Decline: A straight decline means the issuing company has flagged the card as not having sufficient funds, or there is an issue with the card, not the range.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Pin Entry device: This is usually stable but could go after a period of use on the site. Usually easy to spot a defect on this device (keys become still and unusable, it starts freezing up, etc). Please ask the terminal supplier to swap out the problematic device and replace it with a new one.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Issues with Cards on the Point of sale: Where the eft is on the integrated till, Valero will drive card acceptance issue resolution on the POS. Whilst Valero does not have a direct maintenance contract on the POS, Valero does continue to drive issue resolution of issues relating to cards, and the POS suppliers tend to respect that. The two key players here are the suppliers of integrated POS (HTEC and Micros). This is less so for the other POS manufacturers as their systems are not integrated.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Fraud: This is infrequent on Valero sites in the UK, but where it happens, is devastating. Usual fraud is ignoring the authorisation request rejection messages and using manual slips to complete transactions on non-qualifying cards. BMS will penalize the use of manual vouchers, and most fuel card suppliers expect sites to get voice authorizations prior to putting manual transactions through. Where there is a dispute about a card or the amount that was charged to the card, please:<br /><br />\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>Confirm that the transaction went through successfully<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>If it is a manual transaction, was an authorisation code recorded for the transaction? If yes, request a copy of the authorisation code. Fuel card suppliers will kick back and refuse to settle on transactions they have not authorised.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Make sure that manual vouchers have actually been submitted to ATOS.<br /><br /></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Manual voucher process: This process is used by sites when they either have a total failure of OLA, or cannot take cards through their CAD device. To work, the manual voucher process presupposes that:<br /><br />\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>The site is set up to take the card<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>The terminal or CAD has failed, thereby preventing OLA, or<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>The site has lost OLA communications or<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>The card host is down and cannot authorise transaction requests coming through<br />The Manual voucher process allows the site to call the OLA host or the card issuer, get an authorisation code, and run the transaction using the card issuer&rsquo;s voucher.<br /><br />Every site is issued with a stack of vouchers and manual process instructions by the card issuer on joining the network. BMS for instance, provides sites with vouchers, a card imprinter machine, and a number for voice authorisations.&nbsp; On legacy sites, the vouchers are sent to ATOS who send them off to the issuer for settlement.<br /><br />On Gempay sites, ATOS is not involved in the process, so vouchers are sent to individual card issuers or their nominees.<br /><br />The voucher process is not popular because it is time-consuming and takes a while to clear, unlike OLA transactions. There is also a higher risk of fraud on manual transactions as opposed to OLA transactions.<br /><br />It is important to note that the use of a manual process does not deter from the need to have a valid authorisation code. Without that code, the card issuer will not honour the transaction.<br /><br />The key support contacts for each card issuer (see 10.2) will advice on the voice authorisation contact for their cards.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table style=\"height: 409px; width: 687px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" border=\"1\" width=\"658\" cellpadding=\"5\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><strong>Card Type</strong></td>\r\n<td><strong>Host</strong></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">Visa&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br /></span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">Barclaycard</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">Mastercard&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br /></span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">Barclaycard</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">Amex&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br /></span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">American Express</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">Diners&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br /></span></td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left;\"><span style=\"color: #993366;\">Elavon</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">Fastfuel&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br /></span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">UKFuel</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">The Business</span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">UKFuel</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">Euroshell&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br /></span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">Shell (no offline authorisation process, but call 0800 731 3131 for any authorisation issues)</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">BP Routex</span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">BP</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">CHJones&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br /></span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">Keyfuels</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">MyFuel&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <br /></span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">Keyfuels</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">UKFuels Bunker</span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">UKFuels</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\"><span style=\"color: #993366;\">Other bunker ranges</span></span></td>\r\n<td><span style=\"color: #993366;\">TBA</span></td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><span style=\"color: #993366;\">&nbsp;&nbsp; </span><br /><span style=\"color: #000000;\">Figure 5: Card issuers/hosts</span></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><br />The operations manual for each of the fuel card types explains whether they support manual authorisations and can be found in:<br />V:\\IT\\Retail_Systems_Europe\\Information Management Support\\Fuel Card Processes</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: upper-roman;\">\r\n<li>UKFuels and BP offline process:<br /><br />Where the site is unable to run a card through the online authorisation process, either because there is a local technical issue on the site or because the host is unavailable, the site can run a manual and voice authorisation process to accept the cards. This covers most cards except Euroshell cards which cannot be accepted except by online authorisation.<br /><br />\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Capture the transaction details on a manual voucher<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Call the voice authorisation card host (usually the issuer)<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Follow the instructions<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>At the end, the host will provide an authorisation code if the transaction is successful<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Record this on the manual voucher<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Send the voucher to the issuer for settlement</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><br />Details of offline transaction processes for both BP and UKFuel-acquired cards are on the shared site:<br /><br />BP Offline Process:<br />http://intranet.valero.com/IS/UKI1TeamSite/RetailTechnology/Shared%20Documents/BP%20Manual%20Card%20Authorisation%20Process.docx<br /><br />UKFuel (Fastfuel, the Business) offline process:<br />http://intranet.valero.com/IS/UKI1TeamSite/RetailTechnology/Shared%20Documents/UKFuels%20offline%20Authorisation%20Process.docx<br /><br /><strong>Addresses for submitting Manual vouchers:</strong><br /><br />&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table style=\"height: 400px; width: 565px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" border=\"1\" width=\"610\" cellpadding=\"2\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Organisation</td>\r\n<td>Address for submitting manual vouchers</td>\r\n<td>Comment</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Barclays</td>\r\n<td>RR Donnelly<br />Open Sort and Distribute<br />Leicester<br />LE87 2BB<br />Mail Area 113</td>\r\n<td>Use this when the vouchers have not been keyed into the terminal</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Allstar</td>\r\n<td>PO Box 1463 Windmill Hill<br />Swindon<br />SN5 6PS<br /><a href=\"mailto:networkmanagement@allstarcard.co.uk\">networkmanagement@allstarcard.co.uk</a><br />08708423250</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>BP Routex / Fastfuel / Texaco The Business</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<p>Eurocard Centre<br />Herald Park<br />Herald Way<br />Crewe<br />Cheshire</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Legacy Sites</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;1 Trinity Court<br />Wolverhampton<br />WV10 6UH</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>&nbsp;All other cards</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;As advised by the card issuers</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;Retailer to contact the issuer and confirm manual process</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><br /><br /><br /><strong>10.2&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;BARCLAYS OFFLINE PROCESS</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Barclays advises retailers to take cards as chip and pin transactions, requesting online authorisation with every transaction. However where the transaction cannot be accepted as an online transaction either because the Chip on the card cannot be read, or the terminal or communications infrastructure is faulty, or on the occasions that the Online host is unavailable, Barclays will let the retailer accept non-OLA authorised transactions. The rules to follow detailed below are:</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-roman;\">\r\n<li><strong>If the card presented for payment has a chip and the chip does not read:</strong> You may swipe the magnetic stripe through your terminal. Your terminal will automatically prompt you to confirm that the chip cannot be read and then to go online to seek Authorisation. Barclays strongly recommends that the retailer does not progress with the transaction if Authorisation is not obtained, as Barclays will not be able to defend the retailer if the transaction is charged back at a later date:\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>enter the card number embossed on the front of the card using the terminal keys and seek Authorisation</li>\r\n<li>In addition to manually entering the card number into the terminal, imprint a sales voucher and fully complete the verification voucher. This must be signed by the customer. The words &lsquo;For verification only &ndash; this voucher is not for banking&rsquo; should be written on the voucher.<br /><br />The retailer should pass the customer copy to the customer along with the terminal receipt. This is the retailer&rsquo;s proof of transaction and is not for banking as this could lead to the customer being charged twice for the same transaction.<br /><br /></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li><strong>If the terminal is not functioning correctly, or there has been</strong> <strong>a power or telephone network failure</strong>: The site may have to use the imprinter as a backup and complete the transaction using a sales voucher. <br /><br /><span style=\"color: #800080;\"><em><strong>Please remember: An unembossed Visa Electron and Maestro card transaction can only be processed electronically and must not be taken on paper vouchers.</strong></em></span><br /><br /><br />For other Visa card transactions that fall under the category described above, the site is advised to: <br /><br />\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-roman;\">\r\n<li>Carry out all normal checks of the card. Please refer to the card recognition section of this guide.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Place the card face up on the imprinter.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Place the sales voucher, face up, over the card and operate the imprinter.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Remove the sales voucher and card from the imprinter.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Capture&nbsp; the following necessary details:<br /><br />\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-roman;\">\r\n<li>The date</li>\r\n<li>The amount of each item</li>\r\n<li>The transaction total</li>\r\n<li>Details of what was purchased. Please do not just write &lsquo;Goods&rsquo; as this is not acceptable.<br /><br />If the customer is using a purchasing card, they may require a customer reference number to be recorded in the relevant boxes on the sales voucher. Where the product sold is fuel, the &lsquo;For Merchant Use Only&rsquo; boxes on the sales voucher must be used for recording the vehicle registration number. <br /><br /><strong>Please remember</strong>: Altered vouchers are not acceptable.&nbsp; If the retailer makes a mistake when entering the details of a transaction, they&nbsp; must destroy the incorrect voucher and start again. It is essential that vouchers are not pinned, stapled, folded or damaged as this may cause processing problems.<br /><br />The cardholder must sign the sales voucher in the box Indicated, whilst the retailer holds the card and checks&nbsp; that the signature on the sales voucher matches the signature on the reverse of the card.<br />The retailer must also check the signature strip to ensure that no attempt has been made to disguise the original signature.<br /><br /><strong>Please remember</strong>: If here are any suspicions raised by the card, the Retailer must follow the Code 10 procedure.<br /><br />After the signature, the retailer must seek voice Authorisation by calling for authorisation on 0844 822 2000. The site must not split a sale under these circumstances, as split sales will be treated as at site risk and&nbsp; could be charged back if disputed.<br /><br />Retailer will be prompted for the following information when calling for Authorisation:<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Outlet number<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Transaction type &ndash; (&ldquo;Standard Authorisation&rdquo;)<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>The card number embossed on the customer&rsquo;s card<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>The expiry date of the card<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>The issue number if applicable (UK Maestro and Solo cards only)<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>The amount of the transaction (whole pounds only).<br /><br />If the transaction is authorised, Barclays will be give the retailer an authorisation code by a voice response service, which may include numbers and letters. The retailer must write the code in the appropriate box on the sales voucher. Detach the cardholder copy of the sales voucher and hand it to the customer with their card and goods.<br /><br />Should the request be refused, no reason will be given and the retailer should return the card to the customer &ndash; unless instructed otherwise by the operator &ndash; and ask for payment by other means.<br /><br />If the transaction is referred to an operator, site should follow their instructions, and the operator may in fact wish to speak to the cardholder.<br /><br />Once the procedure has been completed and all the required checks have been carried out, retailer must ensure that the necessary details of the transaction have been clearly recorded on all copies of the sales voucher. The retailer should then detach the cardholder copy of the voucher and hand it to the customer with his or her card.<br /><br />Retailer should key in the transaction when the terminal is working again, ensuring the details are correct.<br /><br />If at a later date, the transaction is charged back due to invalid details being input, the site may be debited with a chargeback.<br /><br />If the transaction is accepted, the retailer should file the sales voucher in case of a subsequent dispute. The voucher should not be banked as the retailer&rsquo;s bank account will be credited via the terminal process.<br /><br />However, if when key-entering the transaction, the retailer receives a &lsquo;Declined Authorisation&rsquo; message, the retailer should bank the sales voucher for processing. Transactions may be honoured as long as the retailer has obtained Authorisation where required (i.e. at the time the transaction was undertaken with the cardholder present, and followed all the procedures correctly<br /><br />Retailer must submit the vouchers within 2 days to:</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 150px;\"><span style=\"color: #333399;\"><strong>RR Donnelly</strong></span><br /><span style=\"color: #333399;\"><strong>Open Sort and Distribute</strong></span><br /><span style=\"color: #333399;\"><strong>Leicester</strong></span><br /><span style=\"color: #333399;\"><strong>LE87 2BB</strong></span><br /><span style=\"color: #333399;\"><strong>Mail Area 113</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>10.3&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;SETTLEMENT ISSUES ON THE GEMPAY</strong></p>\r\n<p>There are a number of issues that can drive difficulties in settling on a Gempay site:</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: upper-roman;\">\r\n<li>Terminal allows the wrong ISO: Usually happens with Fuel Cards with both retail and Bunker MIDs. If the terminal is configured with the attributes of the wrong MID, it will allow payments on the wrong card. To resolve,<br /><br />\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>Confirm the correct MID (from the card issuer)</li>\r\n<li>Confirm Card issuer has enabled the MID</li>\r\n<li>Check WREN and HTEC set up reflect the correct MID</li>\r\n<li>If not, request changes where appropriate.</li>\r\n<li>If all systems are showing the right MID:<br /><br />\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-roman;\">\r\n<li>Ask HTEC to correct the attributes to reflect that the MID is not a bunker MID (in the case of fuel cards).</li>\r\n<li>Check with FIS for confirmation that authorisation requests are coming in on that MID. If they are, then the systems are set up and the rejection is coming from the card host (card issuer/acquirer).<br /><br /></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Where the request has come in to update a site MID to a Bunker MID, please:\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>Make sure Karen Goane (Card Manager) has approved the request</li>\r\n<li>Ask HTEC and FIS to update the terminal, TMS and WREN<br /><br /></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Site reports cards are being rejected:\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>Check WREN to confirm the cards have gone through the host</li>\r\n<li>Confirm rejection message: This means it&rsquo;s a card issuer decline, pointing to issues with the card or account.</li>\r\n<li>If there is no rejection message, confirm the card number is valid. If the card is invalid, the terminal will reject it before it goes to the host for authorisation.<br /><br /></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Site payments are delayed or unpaid:<br />Sites are paid on transaction day x 3 for credit/debit card transactions. For an in-depth detail of payment cycles for different card types, please follow the link below:<br /><br />&nbsp;<a href=\"http://intranet.valero.com/IS/UKI1TeamSite/RetailTechnology/Shared%20Documents/Acquirers%20Settlement%20Timings%20September%202013.xlsx\">http://intranet.valero.com/IS/UKI1TeamSite/RetailTechnology/Shared%20Documents/Acquirers%20Settlement%20Timings%20September%202013.xlsx</a><br /><br />Usual causes of delays are the host putting transactions in suspense because they cannot match the transaction messages, or host technical difficulties with submitting the transactions.\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: upper-roman;\">\r\n<li>FIS will usually send out notices showing transactions in suspense either because the site has not done an end of day (get the site to run their end of day),</li>\r\n<li>Or the terminal has failed to treacle its transactions (find out why, could be a fault with the terminal or ADSL). <br />In most cases these are resolved by either asking FIS to release the transactions, or where the terminal is faulty, swapping it out and informing FIS that the terminal is damaged, cannot treacle and requesting the transaction records are settled and released from suspense. This should only be done on advice from HTEC. If the terminal treacles the same data twice, card issuers could charge the customers twice and this is usually very unpleasant to deal with.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><br /><br /><strong>10.4&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;MANAGING TERMINAL WITHDRAWALS:</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">If a terminal is withdrawn, HTEC will send an automated mail to the UK Retail Technology mailbox advising that the terminal has been withdrawn. On receipt of the mail, Valero will send an email to the FIS helpdesk requesting they release the site&rsquo;s transactions currently held awaiting end of day messages. The withdrawn terminal will not trickle and because both old and new terminals have the same TIDs, the site will be left out of pocket if the transactions are not released without the end of day records.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><br /><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"upload/swapoutalert.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"491\" height=\"479\" /><br />&nbsp;<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Figure 6: notice template on terminal recovery</p>\r\n<p><br /><br /><br /><strong>10.5&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;OTHER GEMPAY USUAL SUPPORT ISSUES:</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Gempay is integrating with different Points of sale equipment and this usually raises some support challenges. Typical day to day issues include:</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: upper-roman;\">\r\n<li>Terminals freezing: Causes vary, and the Analyst must work through the systems to make the right determination so the correct fix can be implemented. Usual causes include:\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>Issues with the communications on site, preventing the terminal from making the necessary contacts with the host. Check the router status both on site and TNS online. If there are issues, raise with TNS, escalate to Valero Retail Technology.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Lose cables between the terminal and the point of sale, or the terminal and the router.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>The link between the terminal and the POS can be faulty. Usually an F75 serial link (linked sites), or a notional software link (OPI/Integrated sites), if there is a problem with the link, it is likely that the responses between the terminal and the POS will be flaky or nonexistent.&nbsp; This scenario is likely to affect F75 sites more than OPI sites.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Software issues: OPI sites, affecting the link between the two devices; also potential issues with integrating the two devices, either software or hardware.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Loyalty card when taken out of sequence could drive the terminal to freeze.<br /><br /></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Communications issues: Where ADSL fails on site and the site is unable to get any OLA traffic, GPRS should kick in. There are a few situations where this does not happen automatically:<br /><br />\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-alpha;\">\r\n<li>Where there is still a weak ADSL signal, or the ADSL is &ldquo;flapping&rdquo; in and out of service, the GPRS will still read ADSL as active and will not kick in automatically.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Where the site is in a black spot and cannot get good mobile signals, the GPRS may not kick in automatically.<br /><br />In both instances, it is usually advisable to &ldquo;force&rdquo; GPRS to kick in by removing the ADSL link from the back of the router. This forces the GPRS into service where there is a good service. Sites with perennially bad receptions may get an improved service by deploying an aerial. The UK Retail Technology team holds a stock of these aerials and can supply these to site on request from the helpdesk.<br /><br /><br /><img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"upload/digi-forcegprs.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"642\" height=\"499\" /><br />&nbsp;<br />Figure 7 Digi Router showing Ports</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><br /><br /><strong>10.6&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;SITE CONNECTIVITY TROUBLE SHOOTING</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Connectivity issues are one of the most devastating issues a site can face and are not always easy to identify. In this section, we will outline a few symptoms and hints that may help point an analyst to the fact that the site may be struggling with connectivity.<br />Site network connectivity issues are mostly likely to occur either when:</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-roman;\">\r\n<li>There is a fault on the phone line that hosts the broadband service. <br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>A fault on the broadband service.<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>The Ethernet cable between the terminal and the router is damaged (easy to identify when the issue is connectivity with a single terminal<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>There is however another scenario that is beginning to present a lot on Valero sites. This is where there is a gateway conflict between the Gempay router IP address and the site&rsquo;s own IP Address. This is likely on Micros or HTEC sites where the terminal is working in OPI mode and the site network has a link with the Gempay. The two scenarios are captured below:<br /><br /><br />&nbsp;<img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"upload/ipconflict-noswitch.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"527\" height=\"367\" />Figure 8: IP conflict without a switch</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><br />&nbsp;<img style=\"display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" src=\"upload/ipconflict-switch.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"586\" height=\"364\" />Figure 9: IP Conflict with a Switch</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The networks below are site networks where the site gateway IP address is the same as the Valero Router IP address. In this case, the point of sale equipment is connected to the Valero router and the site&rsquo;s local network either through the site switch or through a direct connection to the Valero router (see figure 6). When transactions are sent for authorisation, the terminal will pick up the two IP addresses and will attempt to send the transaction from the dominant route (site router), and either freeze, or keep reconnecting. Turning off the Valero router will only promote the router temporarily before the site router takes over again. The only way to resolve this is to disconnect the site&rsquo;s back office from the point of sale (temporary solution), or to get the site to change the site&rsquo;s gateway IP address by one octet (192.168.x.253). This issue will arise where the site&rsquo;s Router IP address is 192.168.x.254, exactly the same as the Valero router.<br /><br /><strong>Please note:</strong></p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-roman;\">\r\n<li>Most sites do not know what their IP address is, so do not ask them this question.</li>\r\n<li>Do not ask sites to change their IP address either, as they probably can&rsquo;t and shouldn&rsquo;t.</li>\r\n<li>If you suspect an IP conflict, please raise/escalate to the UK team. The UK team will work with the site to get their router updated.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><br /><strong>Please Note:</strong> The point is to identify what the issue is, and diagnose it adequately. Some simple pointers to what the issue is include:</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: lower-roman;\">\r\n<li>Site is dropping transactions intermittently: This is one of the most common pointers to a network connectivity issue.</li>\r\n<li>One of the terminals works intermittently and the other comes up with &ldquo;reconnecting&rdquo; messages every time the terminal runs a transaction.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table style=\"width: 100%; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" border=\"1\" width=\"653\" cellpadding=\"5\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"155\">\r\n<p><strong>Symptom</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"156\">\r\n<p><strong>Question</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"171\">\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Likely issue</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"172\">\r\n<p><strong>Comment</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"155\">\r\n<p>All cards are declining on all terminals</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"156\">\r\n<p>Is there an ADSL light on the router?<br /> <br /> Is the site a Micros/HTEC OPI site?</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"171\">\r\n<p>No green ADSL light: likely to be an ADSL of line issue<br /> Green light on the router, OPI site: IP conflict</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"172\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Intermittent declines on all cards</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"156\">\r\n<p>Same questions as above</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"171\">\r\n<p>As above</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"172\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Declines on a single scheme</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"156\">\r\n<p>Decline message: card invalid</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"171\">\r\n<p>MID issue</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"172\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Declines on a single scheme</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"156\">\r\n<p>Decline</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"171\">\r\n<p>The card host is likely to be down. Raise with FIS</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"172\">&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"155\">\r\n<p>TNS have fixed the line, but connectivity continues to be intermittent</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"156\">\r\n<p>Is there an ADSL light on the router?<br /> <br /> Is the site a Micros/HTEC OPI site?</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"171\">\r\n<p><strong>On OPI sites:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Causes include either faulty switch<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>IP Conflict<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Micros software gap</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"172\">\r\n<p>Please bear in mind that sometimes there is no easy answer. Eliminate the obvious starting from the easiest Check switch) to mid complexity (check software on POS to ensure compatibility with the Gempay) and IP conflict (sharing device IP address with the site Gateway router)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Intermittent declines on all cards</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"156\">\r\n<p>Is there an ADSL light on the router?</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"171\">\r\n<p>TNS advise they can see nothing wrong, but declines continue on the site.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"172\">\r\n<p>Request an HTEC Engineer:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Check network cables to the router<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Check the ADSL filter<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Check that the router is not overheating, and that there is nothing sitting on top of it<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Reboot the router</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td width=\"155\">\r\n<p>Intermittent declines on all cards</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"156\">\r\n<p>Is there an ADSL light on the router?</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"171\">\r\n<p>TNS advise they can see nothing wrong, but declines continue on the site.</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td width=\"172\">\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Get HTEC to confirm the terminal IP addresses<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Get TNS to look at the router/firewall logs and advice connection attempts from the terminal<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Get HTEC to advise messages on terminal logs and compare with router log messages<br /><br /></li>\r\n<li>Comms error messages on both devices narrows the issue to comms drop out, IP conflict, wrong IP address on the terminals or faulty cables, or router fault</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><br />Figure 10: Network and IP conflict issue id<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><strong>10.7&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;KEY SUPPORT CONTACTS</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The support contacts list is a comprehensive list of all the support organizations and contacts used on the VCS environment. The link below leads to the support contact list:</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">V:\\IT\\Retail_Systems_Europe\\Information Management Support\\support contact list<br />The link has a file called the Retail Technology knowledge base 09 May 2013 v.2. This list is refreshed regularly as contacts change.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><br /><br />TNS Contacts (ADSL):</p>\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type: upper-roman;\">\r\n<li>UK Service Desk 08451112037</li>\r\n<li>Account Support Team/Neil Corker 01142920220</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><br /><br /><br /><strong>10.8&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;TNS ESCALATION AND SEVERITY MATRIX:</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">TNS Weekend/Escalation contacts and Process:</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">When reporting a problem, customers should contact TNS\' International Netowrk Operations Centre INOC at:</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Tel: +44 0114 2920246<br />Email: <a href=\"mailto:eu-networkoperations@tnsi.com\">eu-networkoperations@tnsi.com</a></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">The INOC is staffed 24 hours a day, seven days a week.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">All problem calls will be recorded and issued wit a Trouble Ticket number, which will remain active until the problem is resolved. Customer will be notified upon resolution of the problem, and a written problem report will be supplied upon request.</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">When reporting problems, callers should provide the following information:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Customer contact name, telephone number, and company name</li>\r\n<li>Severity of the outage</li>\r\n<li>A brief but accurate description of the troubleshooting performed prior to calling</li>\r\n<li>The approximate age of the problem</li>\r\n<li>customer router name/id</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table style=\"height: 188px; width: 534px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" border=\"1\" width=\"534\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">Escalation Level</td>\r\n<td>Contact</td>\r\n<td>Contact Number</td>\r\n<td>Notes</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">Fault Report</td>\r\n<td>INOC</td>\r\n<td>0845 1486789<br />+44 0 114 2920246</td>\r\n<td>UK Based Callers<br />International Callers</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">1</td>\r\n<td>Shift Leader</td>\r\n<td>+44 0 114 2920150</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2</td>\r\n<td>INOC Manager</td>\r\n<td>+44 0 114 2920161</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">3</td>\r\n<td>VP Network Operations</td>\r\n<td>+44 0 114 2920200</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">4</td>\r\n<td>UK Managing Director</td>\r\n<td>+44 0 114 2920200</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><br /><strong>SEVERITY MATRIX</strong></p>\r\n<p>Upon logging a call with TNS, the Customer will agree and advise the severity in accordance with the definitions below:-</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table style=\"height: 413px; width: 738px;\" width=\"738\" cellpadding=\"5\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Severity</td>\r\n<td>Definition</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">1</td>\r\n<td>Business impact immediate and major. &nbsp;<br />Production use of the Service is not possible due to the issue and no workaround exists. <br />Complete failure of the service, resulting in severe impact to the operation of the business, customer service and organisational reputation.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2</td>\r\n<td>Business Impact immediate and major but a workaround is in place. &nbsp;<br />Failure of a critical element of the service resulting in a severe impact to a part of the business, or <br />Multiple network connections are down or severely degraded, seriously impacting the Customers&rsquo; business operations, or<br />The Customer requires an urgent response and failure to provide the response will result in severe impact to the operation of the business, customer service and organisational reputation.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">3</td>\r\n<td>A single network connection is down or network functionality is noticeably impaired, but most business operations are able to continue, or<br />Partial or periodic failure of the service, which impacts on the operation of the business, or<br />The Customer requires an answer and failure to provide the response may impact on the operation of the business, customer service and organisational reputation.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">4</td>\r\n<td>Customer requires assistance in-order to investigate existing connectivity. No loss of service experienced, or<br />Partial or periodic failure of the service, which has little or no impact on the operation of the business and where a temporary solution is available, or<br />The Customer requires an answer, but has scope to delay response, minimising the potential impact on the operation of the business.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><br /><br /><br />INCIDENT RESPONSE TIMES</p>\r\n<p>The following table defines the response times associated to the severity of a problem:-</p>\r\n<table style=\"height: 231px; width: 531px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" width=\"381\" cellpadding=\"5\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Severity</td>\r\n<td>Initial Response Time</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>1</td>\r\n<td>Resource assigned immediately and remains assigned (24 x 7) until resolution of the issue.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left;\">2</td>\r\n<td>Resource assigned within 30 minutes and remains assigned (business hours) until resolution of the issue.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left;\">3</td>\r\n<td>Resource assigned within 2 hours.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left;\">4</td>\r\n<td>Resource assigned within 1 day.</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><br /><br />ESCALATION MATRIX<br />The following table indicates the level of escalation internally at TNS in accordance with the severity of the Customer&rsquo;s problem.&nbsp; The times shown indicate the latest point at which each escalation level is made aware of the problem:-<br /><br /></p>\r\n<table style=\"height: 128px; width: 593px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" width=\"593\" cellpadding=\"5\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>Level 1</td>\r\n<td>Level 2</td>\r\n<td>Level 3</td>\r\n<td>Level 4</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">Severity</td>\r\n<td>Shift Leader</td>\r\n<td>Manager</td>\r\n<td>Director, Network Operations</td>\r\n<td>Vice President, Operations</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">1</td>\r\n<td>Immediate</td>\r\n<td>1/2 Hour</td>\r\n<td>2 Hours</td>\r\n<td>4 Hours</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2</td>\r\n<td>1/2 Hour</td>\r\n<td>2 Hours</td>\r\n<td>8 Hours</td>\r\n<td>16 Hours</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">3</td>\r\n<td>4 Hours</td>\r\n<td>8 Hours</td>\r\n<td>16 Hours</td>\r\n<td>48 Hours</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">4</td>\r\n<td>8 Hours</td>\r\n<td>24 Hours</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: left;\">48 Hours</td>\r\n<td>96 Hours</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><br /><br /><br />Severities 1 and 2 refer to elapsed hours, Severities 3 and 4 refer to normal office hours only (9am &ndash; 5.30pm Monday to Friday excluding bank holidays).</p>\r\n<p>Either TNS or the Customer can increase or decrease the Severity provided an appropriate and a valid explanation is provided, and both TNS and Customer agree on the change. The response and resolution timescales will depend on the Severity that is assigned.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>CUSTOMER ESCALATION</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">Should it be necessary, the Customer should call the relevant escalation point on the numbers contained within the Executive Escalation table.&nbsp; All out of working day hours escalations will be carried out through the Shift Leader who will contact the appropriate TNS escalation point.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>EXECUTIVE ESCALATION</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">For Severity 1 &amp; 2 incidents TNS will provide executive escalations, which will be available to the Customer on a 24x7 basis. These details will be provided in the table below:</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table style=\"height: 264px; width: 617px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" width=\"156\" cellpadding=\"5\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Escalation Level</td>\r\n<td>Global Broadband Support</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>1st point of contact</td>\r\n<td>0845 111 2037<br /><br />International: + 44 (0) 114 292 6497<br /><br />eubroadband@tnsi.com</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Level 1 - Shift Leader</td>\r\n<td>EU Payments Duty Shift Supervisor<br /><br />+44 (0) 114 292 0150<br /><br />EU-NetworkOperationsShiftLeaders@tnsi.com</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Level 2 - Manager</td>\r\n<td>Richard Potts &ndash; Manager, EU Network Operations<br /><br />+44 (0) 114 292 0161<br /><br />rpotts@tnsi.com</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Level 3 - Director</td>\r\n<td>Craig Russell &ndash; Director, EU Network Operations<br /><br />+44 (0) 114 292 0195<br /><br />crussell@tnsi.com</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Level 4 - VP</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;Ciaran Jones &ndash; VP, EU Network Operations<br /><br />+44 (0) 114 292 0225<br /><br />cajones@tnsi.com</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Service Management</td>\r\n<td>\r\n<table style=\"height: 111px;\" width=\"468\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Tim Iannetta &ndash; Service Manager<br /><br />+44 (0) 20 7336 1524<br /><br />0754 551 4359<br /><br />tiannetta@tnsi.com</td>\r\n<td>Change Management<br /><br />+44 0114 307 0612<br /><br />Intl.ops.change.mgt@tnsi.com</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">TNS&rsquo; trouble ticket system will be used to log all problems and provide update reports to the Customer. The call will then be assigned to a team within TNS to investigate and resolve. &nbsp;<br /><br />TNS will log all details of the fault/problem including a Severity rating between the Customer and TNS.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>INCIDENT REPORTING</strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\">For Severity 1 &amp; 2 incidents, when requested by the Customer, TNS will produce an Incident Report in accordance with the following table:</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<table style=\"height: 65px; width: 392px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" width=\"392\" cellpadding=\"5\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">Severity</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">Incident Report Delivery Target</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">1 (URGENT)</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">3 days</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">2 (HIGH)</td>\r\n<td style=\"text-align: center;\">5 Days</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><br />In relation to the Incident Report Delivery Target, &ldquo;Days&rdquo; are defined as business days, excluding weekends and public holidays, &ldquo;day 1&rdquo; being the day following the permanent resolution of the fault. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><br /><br /><strong>10.8.1&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;BT ISDN Support contacts:</strong></p>\r\n<table style=\"height: 165px; width: 771px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\" border=\"1\" width=\"734\" cellpadding=\"5\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Contact Area</td>\r\n<td>Name</td>\r\n<td>Contact Number</td>\r\n<td>Email</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Billing 1st Point of Escalation</td>\r\n<td>Michelle Wyse-Polson</td>\r\n<td>0800 622070</td>\r\n<td>michelle.wyse-polson@bt.com</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>All Billing Enquiries</td>\r\n<td>Bournemouth</td>\r\n<td>0800 622 070</td>\r\n<td>bmbilling01@bt.com</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Faults Team</td>\r\n<td>UK Volume Assurance</td>\r\n<td>0800 1217667</td>\r\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td>Service Delivery Centre / Team</td>\r\n<td>Customer Order Team</td>\r\n<td>0808 100 7499 (opt 1, opt 1)</td>\r\n<td>Orders.glasgow1@bt.com</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>', '2014-07-29 12:36:27', 'l7d23b', '2016-05-27 08:38:52', 'l7d23b', 'yes', 'no', '', '', '0000-00-00 00:00:00', 'Card Systems Operations and Maintenance Manual', '', 80002, 'UK Support 1', 'N', 'mailto:networkmanagement@allstarcard.co.ukhttp://intranet.valero.com/IS/UKI1TeamSite/RetailTechnology/Shared Documents/Acquirers Settlement Timings September 2013.xlsxmailto:eu-networkoperations@tnsi.com');
